# 2.1 Strings

## Create Strings

```python
name = "Connor"
name = 'Connor'
empty = ""
user_input = input()
```

## String Basics

- Strings are sequences of characters.
- Indexing starts at `0`.
- Strings are immutable (cannot change individual characters).

## Length

```python
len(name)
```

## Indexing

```python
name[0]      # First character
name[-1]     # Last character
```

## Concatenation

```python
first = "New"
second = "York"

city = first + second       # NewYork
city = first + " " + second # New York
```

---

# 2.2 Lists

## Create Lists

```python
numbers = [5, 10, 20]
mixed = [1, 2.5, "abc"]
empty_list = []
```

## List Basics

- Ordered collection.
- Mutable (can be changed).
- Can contain mixed data types.

## Access Elements

```python
numbers[0]
numbers[-1]
```

## Modify Elements

```python
numbers[1] = 99
```

## Add and Remove

```python
numbers.append(50)      # Add to end
numbers.pop(1)          # Remove by index
numbers.remove(99)      # Remove by value
```

## Useful Functions

```python
len(numbers)
sum(numbers)
min(numbers)
max(numbers)
```

## Useful Methods

```python
numbers.index(10)
numbers.count(10)
```

## Concatenate Lists

```python
list3 = list1 + list2
```

---

# 2.3 Dictionaries

## Create Dictionaries

```python
ages = {"Bob": 27, "Frank": 75}
empty_dict = {}
```

## Dictionary Basics

- Stores key-value pairs.
- Mutable.
- Keys must be immutable.
- Values can be any type.

## Access Values

```python
ages["Bob"]
```

## Add or Update

```python
ages["Alice"] = 30
ages["Bob"] = 28
```

## Delete

```python
del ages["Bob"]
```

